  <section>
    <h2>üîç Evaluating Content Quality</h2>
    <p>Use these criteria to evaluate whether content is truly educational:</p>

    <h3>Quality Educational Content:</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>‚úÖ Age-appropriate and curriculum-aligned</li>
      <li>‚úÖ Teaches specific skills or knowledge</li>
      <li>‚úÖ Interactive and engaging (not just passive watching)</li>
      <li>‚úÖ No ads or minimal, appropriate ads</li>
      <li>‚úÖ Evidence-based and accurate information</li>
      <li>‚úÖ Encourages critical thinking</li>
      <li>‚úÖ Created by educators or experts</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Red Flags (Low-Quality "Edutainment"):</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>‚ùå Excessive ads or in-app purchases</li>
      <li>‚ùå Auto-play to unrelated content</li>
      <li>‚ùå Oversimplified or inaccurate information</li>
      <li>‚ùå Focus on memorization over understanding</li>
      <li>‚ùå Designed to maximize screen time, not learning</li>
      <li>‚ùå Inappropriate themes disguised as "educational"</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Check Reviews & Ratings:</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Common Sense Media</strong> - Excellent resource for age-appropriate reviews</li>
      <li><strong>Teacher/parent reviews</strong> - Real feedback from educators</li>
      <li><strong>App Store educational rankings</strong> - Look for "Editors' Choice"</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>üí° Making Educational Content Appealing</h2>

    <h3>Strategies to Increase Buy-In:</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Let them choose:</strong> "Pick 3 Khan Academy subjects you want to explore"</li>
      <li><strong>Gamify it:</strong> Track progress, set goals, offer rewards</li>
      <li><strong>Match interests:</strong> Love dinosaurs? Watch paleontology documentaries</li>
      <li><strong>Make it social:</strong> Co-view and discuss together</li>
      <li><strong>Show real-world application:</strong> "Learn coding to make your own game"</li>
      <li><strong>Leverage YouTube:</strong> Educational channels can be as engaging as entertainment</li>
      <li><strong>Creative projects:</strong> "Make a video documentary about your research"</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Avoid These Mistakes:</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>‚ùå Using educational content as punishment</li>
      <li>‚ùå Forcing boring, low-quality "educational" apps</li>
      <li>‚ùå Never allowing any entertainment</li>
      <li>‚ùå Lecturing about how "this is good for you"</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>üìä Tracking the Balance</h2>

    <h3>Simple Tracking System:</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>Use built-in screen time reports (iOS/Android) to see what apps are used</li>
      <li>Create categories: Educational, Hybrid, Entertainment</li>
      <li>Review weekly: "Let's look at your screen time report together"</li>
      <li>Discuss: "I see lots of YouTube - was that educational or entertainment?"</li>
      <li>Adjust: "Next week, let's try more balanced mix"</li>
    </ol>

    <h3>Visual Tracking (for Younger Kids):</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Use a chart with stickers: Green for educational, yellow for hybrid, red for entertainment</li>
      <li>Goal: More green stickers than red each week</li>
      <li>Reward meeting goals with special activity (not more screen time)</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>üéÆ Special Cases</h2>

    <h3>What About Gaming?</h3>
    <p>Games exist on a spectrum:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Educational:</strong> Prodigy Math, CodeCombat, DragonBox</li>
      <li><strong>Educational-ish:</strong> Minecraft (creative mode), Civilization, Portal (problem-solving)</li>
      <li><strong>Entertainment:</strong> Fortnite, Call of Duty, mobile games</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Apply 80/20 rule to gaming specifically if it's a major time investment.</p>

    <h3>What About Social Media?</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Generally entertainment, but can be educational if following educational accounts</li>
      <li>Curate feed: Follow science communicators, educational institutions, skill-share creators</li>
      <li>Limit mindless scrolling, encourage purposeful use</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>What About YouTube?</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>100% depends on content</li>
      <li>Review subscriptions together</li>
      <li>Encourage educational channels: Mark Rober, Vsauce, Veritasium, SmarterEveryDay</li>
      <li>Limit algorithm-driven browsing (auto-play leads to low-quality)</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

